Lab 2

Problem 1: Î³-Ray Detection

We are looking for gamma-ray sources with a telescope similar to the Fermi telescope. In this kind of telescope there is a background of cosmic-rays (electrons and protons, mostly) that provides a discrete noise term across the sky that precisely follows a Poisson distribution. To detect a gamma-ray source, you need to ask what is the probability that the cosmic-ray background would have given you a measurement as signal-like or more than the signal that you received.

A) Progression of Probability Distribution after Integration over Days

Taking my average cosmic ray background as X = 2.6 and the average number of emmissions from my source as Y = 5.9. Both averages are for 1 day.
X = 2.6;
Y = 5.9;
Generating my background distribution (Poisson):
xvals = 0:10;
poisson = makedist("Poisson","lambda",X);
funct = pdf(poisson,xvals);
subplot(1,2,1)
stairs(xvals-0.5,funct,"LineWidth",3)
title('Background Poisson Distribution')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
%semi-log axis
subplot(1,2,2)
stairs(xvals-0.5,funct,"LineWidth",3)
set(gca,'YScale','log')
title('Semi-log Background')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('log(y)')
Summing the distribution over 4 days:
resolution = 1;
xmax = 10;
xmin = 0;
x = xmin:resolution:xmax;
logP = makedist("Poisson",'lambda',X);
base = pdf(logP,x);
base = base/sum(base);
comb = base;
subplot(1,1,1)
stairs(x,base)
hold on
for h = 2:4
comb = conv(comb,base,"full");
cx = xmin*h:resolution:xmax*h;
stairs(cx,comb)
end
hold off
legend('Day 1','Day 2','Day 3','Day 4')
title('Summed Distribution (Day 1 - Day 4)')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
The graph shows how the distribution progresses over several days. As time passes, the summed distribution flattens out, moves to the right, and begins to appear more Gaussian.
comb = base;
subplot(2,2,1)
stairs(x,base,"LineWidth",3)
title('Summed N = 1, linear')
for i = 2:4
comb = conv(comb,base,"full");
subplot(2,2,i)
cx = xmin*i:resolution:xmax*i;
stairs(cx,comb,"LineWidth",3)
title(['Summed N = ',num2str(i),', linear'])
end
Here you see the distributions individually.

B) Probability Distribution after 5 Days

Convolving my distribution 5 times to model the background distribution on day 5:
X = 2.6;
Y = 5.9;
res = 1;
xmax_5 = 10;
xmin_5 = 0;
x = xmin_5:res:xmax_5;
logP = makedist("Poisson",'lambda',X);
base = pdf(logP,x);
base = base/sum(base);
comb = base;
for j = 2:5
comb = conv(comb,base,"full");
end
subplot(1,1,1)
cx_5 = xmin_5*j:res:xmax_5*j;
stairs(cx_5,comb,"LineWidth",3)
title('Summed N = 5')
hold on
weighted_5 = zeros(1,length(cx_5));
for k = 1:length(cx_5)
weighted_5(k) = comb(k)*cx_5(k);
end
lambda = sum(weighted_5);
poisson_5 = makedist("Poisson","lambda",lambda);
plot(cx_5,pdf(poisson_5,cx_5),"LineWidth",3)
legend('Summed','Poisson Overlay')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
hold off
I've overlayed a poisson distribution with the same average value "lambda" as I calculated from my Day 5 distribution. It matches perfectly with the convolution, indicating that the distribution remains a Poisson distribution even after summing over 5 days.
This makes sense, since during the summation, all of the data points follow Poisson distributions, without manipulation of any axes.
Explain why this makes sense from a mathematical and conceptual point of view

C) Progression of Probability Distribution Averaged over 7 Days

X = 2.6;
Y = 5.9;
res = 1;
xmax = 10;
xmin = 0;
x = xmin:res:xmax;
logP = makedist("Poisson",'lambda',X);
day1 = pdf(logP,x);
day1 = day1/sum(day1);
dayn = day1;
stairs(x,day1,"LineWidth",1)
hold on
for i = 2:7
dayn = conv(dayn,day1,"full");
x_n = xmin:res/i:xmax;
stairs(x_n,i*dayn,"LineWidth",1)
end
title('Averaged Distributions (Day 1 - Day 7)')
legend('Day 1','Day 2','Day 3','Day 4','Day 5','Day 6','Day 7')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
I average the distribution by dividing my resolution, "res" by the number of convolutions. I ensure the area under the curve is still 1 by plotting my graph with y-values of "i*dayn".
The graph above shows how the distribution changes over many days. It starts out as the initial Poisson distribution and narrows with each convolution, becoming more Gaussian. In (B) we saw the distribution appear more Gaussian but still follow a Poisson distribution. Here, because we average the x-axis, the distribution maintains its location on the graph but becomes taller and closer to a normal distribution.
This progression is predicted by the Central Limit Theorem, which states that regardless of the initial distribution, if it is averaged enough it will become a Gaussian distribution.
hold off
day1 = pdf(logP,x);
day1 = day1/sum(day1);
dayn = day1;
for i = 2:7
dayn = conv(dayn,day1,"full");
subplot(3,2,i-1)
x_n = xmin:res/i:xmax;
stairs(x_n,i*dayn,"LineWidth",3)
title(['Averaged N = ',num2str(i),', linear'])
end
hold off
In these plots, you can see the average distribution over 2 through 7 days individually.

D) Sigma of Y*N Î³-Rays for N = 8 Days

N = 8 days.
N = 8;
gammas = Y*N;
To calculate the sigma for Y*N gamma rays, I have to find the probability of Y*N on the summed distribution for 8 days. Once I have that probability, I can use norminv to find my sigma value.
day1 = pdf(logP,x);
day1 = day1/sum(day1);
dayn = day1;
for i = 2:8
dayn = conv(dayn,day1,"full");
cx_N = xmin*i:res:xmax*i;
end
weighted_N = zeros(1,length(cx_N));
for k = 1:length(cx_N)
weighted_N(k) = dayn(k)*cx_N(k);
end
lambda = sum(weighted_N);
p = cdf("Poisson",gammas,lambda);
sigma = norminv(p)
sigma =
5.037815760646996
So my sigma is just over .

Problem 2: Rayleigh Convolutions

A) Averaging a Continuous Distribution

For this problem, I've chosen to use a Rayleigh distribution with parameter 2 which, unlike the Poisson in problem 1, is continuous.
ray_res = 0.1;
xmax = 10;
xmin = 0;
x = xmin:ray_res:xmax;
ray = makedist("Rayleigh",'b',2);
base_ray = pdf(ray,x);
base_ray = base_ray/sum(base_ray);
avgd = base_ray;
subplot(1,1,1)
plot(x,base_ray)
hold on
for i = 2:7
avgd = conv(avgd,base_ray,"full");
x_k = xmin:ray_res/i:xmax;
plot(x_k,i*avgd,"LineWidth",1)
end
title('Averaged Rayleigh (Day 1 - Day 7)')
legend('Day 1','Day 2','Day 3','Day 4','Day 5','Day 6','Day 7')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
This graph shows the progression of the distributions in comparison to one another. The distribution starts as a typical Rayleigh, skewed to one side, and progressively becomes narrower, more uniform, and more Gaussian.
avgd = base_ray;
subplot(2,3,1)
plot(x,base_ray,"LineWidth",3)
title('Averaged N = 1, linear')
for k = 2:6
avgd = conv(avgd,base_ray,"full");
subplot(2,3,k)
x_k = xmin:ray_res/k:xmax;
plot(x_k,k*avgd,"LineWidth",3)
title(['Averaged N = ',num2str(k),', linear'])
end
These graphs show the progression from the initial Rayleigh to the 6th average.

B) Becoming a Gaussian?

In the following graphs, I've overlayed a Gaussian distribution to compare with the averaged distribution over several intervals.
ray_res = 0.1;
xmax = 10;
xmin = 0;
x = xmin:ray_res:xmax;
ray = makedist("Rayleigh","b",2);
base_ray = pdf(ray,x);
base_ray = base_ray/sum(base_ray);
avgd = base_ray;
gaussian_dist = makedist("Normal","mu",2.5,"sigma",0.5);
gauss = pdf(gaussian_dist,x)/sum(pdf(gaussian_dist,x));
subplot(1,1,1)
plot(x,base_ray,"LineWidth",2)
hold on
plot(x,gauss,"LineWidth",2)
hold off
title('Rayleigh vs. Gaussian')
legend('Rayleigh','Gaussian')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
for k = 2:7
avgd = conv(avgd,base_ray,"full");
subplot(2,3,k-1)
x_k = xmin:ray_res/k:xmax;
plot(x_k,k*avgd,"LineWidth",2)
hold on
plot(x,gauss,"LineWidth",2)
hold off
title(['N = ',num2str(k),', linear'])
end
avgd = base_ray;
for j = 2:7
avgd = conv(avgd,base_ray,"full");
subplot(2,3,j-1)
x_k = xmin:ray_res/j:xmax;
plot(x_k,j*avgd,"LineWidth",2)
hold on
plot(x,gauss,"LineWidth",2)
set(gca,'YScale','log')
hold off
title(['N = ',num2str(j),', semi-log'])
end
In both the regular and semi-log axis plots, as the distribution is averaged more, the distribution changes to become closer to the Gaussian distribution. After only seven averages, the regular plot is almost exactly Gaussian, though the semi-log plot still shows some differences.

Problem 3: Gravity-Wave Signal Detection

The discovery of optical/infra-red counterparts of Neutron star mergers initially detected with gravity-waves is one of the great discoverys in the last few years, and has ushered in the age of "multi-messenger astrophysics."
We're going to explore one of the analysis questions that comes up when looking for the optical counterparts (a new optical source) of a gravity wave signal. Assume that we are using an optical telescope with a thermal noise background from the CCD (dark current, particularly an issue with older CCDs and/or infra-red CCDs). After flat-fielding, the background appears as a zero-mean Gaussian with constant width over the image.

Version 1

You have an alert from LIGO that is also seen in with the X-ray/ultra-violet satellite SWIFT. SWIFT gives you a very precise location, so you take an image of that part of the sky. But because of SWIFT's accuracy, you know which pixel in your image to look for a counterpart in.

A) Significance of Signal Detection of Strength Y = 5.36

X = 1.06;
Y = 4.56;
xes = -5:0.1:5;
subplot(1,1,1)
background = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",X);
bg = pdf(background,xes);
plot(xes,bg,"LineWidth",3)
title('Gaussian Background Distribution, linear')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
background = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",X);
bg = pdf(background,xes);
plot(xes,bg,"LineWidth",3)
set(gca,'YScale','log')
title('Gaussian Background Distribution, semi-log')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('log(y)')
prob = cdf(background,Y)
prob =
0.999991532508253
% cdf integrates from -infinity to Y, which is why it's so close to 1.
% Plugging in -Y would give the probability from Y to infinity, since this
% is a Gaussian distribution.
sigma = norminv(prob)
sigma =
4.301886792453057
Typically, a sigma value of or more is considered significant. Since my sigma value is about , it is not considered to be a significant detection.

Version 2

You have an alert from LIGO, but no associated detection from SWIFT. This could be because it is a black hole-black hole merger, a black hole-neutron star merger (neither seem to emit X-rays or UV light), or it could because SWIFT was indisposed at the time (wrong side of the earth in its orbit). Whatever the cause, you know what region of the sky to look in, but not which pixel.

B) Probability Distribution of the Background for 10k Pixels

Convolving my distribution 10,000 times takes way too long, so to find the background distribution, I can use some knowledge of convolutions and of probability.
My question: Given a set of 10,000 pixels, what does my background distribution look like and how likely is it that the background will look as or more signal-like than my signal? In this background, is my signal significant?
To give a vague impression of what 10,000 convolutions would look like, I'll convolve my distribution 10 times and see how the standard deviation and probability compares to my initial distribution.
pd = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",1.06);
x = -5:0.1:5;
funct = pdf(pd,x);
funct = funct/sum(funct);
combined = funct;
prob = cdf(pd,-Y)
prob =
8.467491746664095e-06
% I'm choosing to use -4.56 since the gaussian distribution is symmetric, so
% probability of -4.56 is equal to the probability of 1 - p(4.56). This will
% minimize error and be useful in section C. Here, prob gives the
% probability of detecting a signal equal to or greater than 4.56, integrating from
% 4.56 to infinity.
for i = 2:10
combined = conv(combined,funct,"full");
end
subplot(1,1,1)
standard_dev = std(combined)
standard_dev =
0.002723384906358
cbx = -5:0.1/10:5;
plot(cbx,combined*10,"LineWidth",3)
title('Background after 10 Convolutions, linear')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('y')
cbx = -5:0.1/10:5;
plot(cbx,combined*10,"LineWidth",3)
set(gca,'YScale','log')
title('Background after 10 Convolutions, semi-log')
xlabel('x')
ylabel('log(y)')
As you can see, even after only 10 convolutions, the graph of the distribution is much thinner than before, with a standard deviation of 0.003. This indicates that, since the distribution will become thinner with each convolution, the background after 10,000 convolutions will essentially be a sharp peak at 0, with very little width. The semi-log plot also became thinner, and has a more rounded distribution.

C) Significance of Y in 10k Pixels

On probability, since we want to find the significance of the brightest candidate signal (Y), we have to calculate the probability of that Y in 10,000 pixels. The probability of detecting a signal greater than or equal to 4.56 is in the realm of . We can assume that each convolution will cause that probability to become prob*n, using the "or" probability calculation where is sufficiently small that we can ignore it.
Therefore, the probability of detecting that signal Y in 10,000 pixels is 10,000*prob(Y). We can use that probability to find the sigma value.
prob_pix = 10000*prob
prob_pix =
0.084674917466641
sigma_pix = -norminv(prob_pix)
sigma_pix =
1.374295912000969
So our sigma value in 10,000 pixes is , which is not very significant at all.

Problem 4: Inversion

The statistical issue we were exploring in the previous problem is called a trials factor (sometimes known as a look-elsewhere effect). This is an important effect, as if you search through a million locations, you would expect to see ~1 one in a million event. However, it is also often over estimated how big an impact this makes on the sensitivity of a search. So in this part of the lab we are going to invert the problem.
Let us again assume we have a Gaussian background (same parameters as Problem 3).

A) Signal required for a 5-sigma detection in Version 1

Background Distribution:
X = 1.06;
Y = 3.56;
xes = -5:0.1:5;
background = makedist("Normal","mu",0,"sigma",X);
bg = pdf(background,xes);
Calculating signal from sigma:
sig = 5;
p_calcd = normcdf(-5)
p_calcd =
2.866515718791946e-07
Norm cdf gives the probability of some value x on a standard normal distribution, which has a mean on 0 and a standard deviation of 1. I can therefore just plug in my sigma value as x to find the corresponding probability, which turns out to be p_5 = 0.9999997...
signal = -icdf(background,p_calcd)
signal =
5.300000000000001
So I would need a signal of about 5.3 for a detection.

B) Signal required for a 5-sigma detection in Version 2

sig_2 = 5;
p_2 = normcdf(-sig_2)
p_2 =
2.866515718791946e-07
My process in 3C was to multiply the probability by 10,000 due to the number of pixels, so here I divide my probability value by 10,000. I also take the normcdf of the negative sigma value to get the correct probability.
p_calcd_2 = p_2/10000
p_calcd_2 =
2.866515718791946e-11
signal_2 = -icdf(background,p_calcd_2)
signal_2 =
6.943569869467655
I would need a signal of about 6.9.

C) Comparison of Signal Brightness for 1 and 10k Pixels

For a single pixel, I need a signal of 5.3 for detection as opposed to a signal of 6.9 for 10k pixels.
ratio = signal_2/signal
ratio =
1.310107522541067
The 10k signal has to be 1.3 times brighter than the single pixel signal. The sensitivity penalty is so low due to the fact that the measured signals are on the fringes of the distribution. The probability for 1 pixel is ~ and for 10k pixels it's ~. Compared to signals with probabilities closer to near the mean, the probabilities are very small, and their differences are less significant. The closer to the mean the signal, the more sensitivity it will have to an increase in amount of pixels.

D) Effect of Significan Trials Factor Changes on Sensitivity Threshold

Changing the trials factor in this context means changing the amount of pixels. Here are two examples of different orders of magnitude:
  1. 100 pixels
p_calcd_100 = p_2/100
p_calcd_100 =
2.866515718791946e-09
signal_100 = -icdf(background,p_calcd_100)
signal_100 =
6.173826417178940
ratio = signal_100/signal
ratio =
1.164872908901687
2. pixels
p_calcd_109 = p_2/(10^9)
p_calcd_109 =
2.866515718791946e-16
signal_109 = -icdf(background,p_calcd_109)
signal_109 =
8.580551453950120
ratio = signal_109/signal
ratio =
1.618971972443419
For 100, 1000, and even pixels, the ratio of signals to the signal for 1 pixel is less than 2. The effect on the sensitivity threshold is fairly small.
